    "summary": "Kristallnacht (Night of Broken Glass) was a coordinated nationwide pogrom against Jewish Germans carried out on the nights of November 9–10, 1938, organized by the Nazi Party and SS. The pretext was the assassination of a German diplomat in Paris by Herschel Grynszpan, a young Jewish man whose family had been among thousands of Polish Jews expelled from Germany. Over two days, approximately 7,500 Jewish-owned businesses were destroyed, around 1,400 synagogues were burned or vandalized, nearly 100 Jews were killed directly, and approximately 30,000 Jewish men were arrested and sent to concentration camps. The name derived from the vast quantities of broken glass from shop windows littering German streets.\n\nKristallnacht represented a major escalation in the [[event:2653|Nazi regime's]] persecution of Jews, moving from legal discrimination and economic exclusion toward open organized violence. The Nazi authorities subsequently held the Jewish community collectively responsible and imposed a fine of one billion Reichsmarks as punishment for the destruction. Jews were forced out of the German economy and barred from schools. The events prompted an accelerated wave of Jewish emigration from Germany and Austria — those who could leave did so with increasing urgency.\n\nKristallnacht is now understood as a critical step on the path toward the [[event:2660|Holocaust]]. Its open, nationwide nature demonstrated how far the regime was willing to go and how thoroughly it had normalized antisemitic violence. The international response was largely one of condemnation without concrete action to accept Jewish refugees, a failure with severe consequences.",
